'''John Owen, Jr.''' (August 18, 1861 – August 1924<ref name=Voyles>{{cite book|last=Voyles|first=Kenneth H.|author2-last=Rodrique|author2-first=Mary|title=The Enduring Legacy of the Detroit Athletic Club: Driving the Motor City|year=2012|publisher=[[The History Press]]|pages=23–26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9k-M1lgAYhAC&pg=PA23}}</ref>) was an American athlete and businessman. He was born in [[Detroit]],<ref>[http://www.onlinebiographies.info/mi/wayne/owen-j.htm Biography of John Owen]</ref> and took up athletics in 1889 at the ages of 28. Owen was discovered and coached by [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]] at the [[Detroit Athletic Club]]. In 1890, he ran the [[100-yard dash]] in a world record time of 9.8 seconds.<ref name=Guarding>{{cite news|title=The Good Trust Guarding Thirty Thousand Collegians|newspaper=Ft. Wayne Sentinel|date=1911-10-28}}</ref> Owen died in 1924 after a horseback riding accident at his summer home on [[Mackinac Island]].<ref name=Voyles />

