'''Benkato''' "'''Kato'''" '''Ottio'''<ref name=volley /><ref name="Amoa NCD" /> (20 March 1994 – 9 January 2018) was a [[Papua New Guinea]]n [[rugby league]] footballer. Primarily playing as a [[Centre (rugby league)|centre]], Ottio represented the [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinean national team]], most notably at the [[2017 Rugby League World Cup|2017 World Cup]].

==Early life==
Ottio was born and raised in the village of [[Tatana Island|Tatana]], near [[Port Moresby]], [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ritchie|first=Dean|date=7 December 2016|title=Kato Ottio goes from PNG volleyball team to Canberra Raiders NRL side|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/raiders/kato-ottio-goes-from-png-volleyball-team-to-canberra-raiders-nrl-side/news-story/6a5f194ae06151d05accd20d261d3318|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref> 

Before playing rugby league, Ottio played [[volleyball]] and was a member of PNG's squad at the [[2013 Pacific Mini Games]] in [[Wallis and Futuna]], which won gold,<ref name="Josiah Abavu">{{cite web|last=Ami|first=Jack|date=17 February 2016|title=Ottio up for Raiders trial|url=http://www.thenational.com.pg/ottio-up-for-raiders-trial/|publisher=The National (PNG)|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref> and Amoa NCD's team at the [[2014 Asian Men's Club Volleyball Championship]] in the [[Philippines]].<ref name="Amoa NCD">{{cite web|title=PNG • AMOA NCD: Players|url=http://www.asianvolleyball.net/bulletin/1617029997_1397186501.pdf|publisher=Asian Volleyball|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref name="Canberra signing">{{cite web|last=Gaskin|first=Lee|date=26 February 2016|title=Canberra Raiders sign PNG international Kato Ottio for two years|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/nrl-canberra-raiders-sign-png-international-kato-ottio-to-twoyear-contract-20160225-gn4662.html|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref> Ottio then took up rugby league exclusively, playing at an amateur level for the [[Dobo Warriors]].<ref name="Josiah Abavu" />

==Playing career==
===Early career===
In October 2014, Ottio played for the PNG Prime Minister's XIII against the Australian [[Prime Minister's XIII]], which saw him subsequently sign with the [[Papua New Guinea Hunters]] of the [[Queensland Cup]], starting in 2015.<ref name="Josiah Abavu" /> Ottio made his debut for the national side in May 2015 against [[Fiji national rugby league team|Fiji]]. In February 2016, Ottio signed a two-year contract with the [[Canberra Raiders]],<ref name="Canberra signing" /> spending the duration with the Raiders' feeder team, the [[Mount Pritchard Mounties]], in the [[New South Wales Cup]]. He was named on the wing in the 2016 NSW Cup Team of the Year, having scored 29 tries in 23 games,<ref>{{cite web|date=22 September 2016|title=2016 ISP NSW Team of the Year|url=http://www.nswrl.com.au/news/2016/09/22/_2016_intrust_super_.html|publisher=NSWRL.com.au|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref> the [[New South Wales Rugby League]]'s leading tryscorer in 2016.<ref name="abc9jan">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-01-09/png-rugby-league-player-kato-ottio-dies/9313838 |title=Papua New Guinea rugby league player Kato Ottio dies after falling ill at training |work=ABC News |date=9 January 2018 |accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> Ottio was not considered for PNG's May 2017 match against the [[Cook Islands national rugby league team|Cook Islands]] as he had recently returned from a long-term injury.<ref>{{cite web|date=1 May 2017|title=NRL stars missing from Pacific Test squads|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/329822/sport-nrl-stars-missing-from-pacific-test-squads|publisher=Radio NZ|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref> In October 2017, Ottio was named in PNG's squad for the [[2017 Rugby League World Cup|2017 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dutton|first=Chris|date=4 October 2017|title=Kurt Baptiste and Kato Ottio picked in Papua New Guinea squad for World Cup|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/rugby-league/canberra-raiders/kurt-baptiste-and-kato-ottio-picked-in-papua-new-guinea-squad-for-world-cup-20171003-gytvi6.html|publisher=Canberra Times|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref>

===Widnes Vikings===
In December 2017, Ottio signed with the [[Widnes Vikings]] who play in the [[Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|date=1 December 2017|title=Widnes sign centre Kato Ottio from Canberra Raiders|url=http://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/news/12228/11151394/widnes-sign-centre-kato-ottio-from-canberra-raiders|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Helmers|first=Caden|date=2 December 2017|title=Former Canberra Raiders winger Kato Ottio signs with Widnes|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/former-canberra-raiders-winger-kato-ottio-signs-with-widnes-20171202-gzxct7.html|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>

==International caps==
Ottio won six caps for the national side, known as the Kumuls. His debut was in May 2015 against [[Fiji national rugby league team|Fiji]] at the [[Robina Stadium]], [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]]. A second cap, also against Fiji came a year later and Ottio scored his debut international try at the [[Parramatta Stadium]] in [[Sydney]]. Selected for the Kumuls squad for the 2017 World Cup, he played in all three of the team's [[2017 Rugby League World Cup Group C|group games]] played in Port Moresby and scored a try in the game against [[Wales national rugby league team|Wales]].  His final international game was the quarter-final defeat to [[England national rugby league team|England]] at the [[Melbourne Rectangular Stadium]].<ref name=RLP/>

==Death==
Ottio collapsed due to [[heat stroke]] while training alongside the [[Papua New Guinea Hunters]] on 7 January 2018, and died in the early hours of 9 January suffering from [[internal bleeding]].<ref name="abc9jan"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Bauai|first=Gloria|date=9 January 2018|title=Ottio succumbed to heat stroke|url=http://www.looppng.com/sport/ottio-succumbed-heat-stroke-72032|publisher=Loop PNG|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> He had been due to travel to the United Kingdom to join the Widnes squad for pre-season training on 11 January.<ref>{{cite web|date=8 January 2018|title=Kato Ottio: Widnes Vikings & Papua New Guinea centre, 23, dies|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/rugby-league/42615127|publisher=BBC|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Walter|first=Brad|title=Players struggling with Ottio death after training collapse|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/01/09/players-struggling-with-Kato-ottio-death-after-training-collapse/|publisher=NRL.com|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> Ottio's funeral was held on 12 January at [[Sir John Guise Stadium|Sir John Guise Indoor Complex]], and was attended by the [[Prime Minister of Papua New Guinea]], [[Peter O'Neill]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=David|date=12 January 2018|title=Kato Ottio rejected Dragons deal so he could join PNG in RLWC|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/kato-ottio-rejected-dragons-deal-so-he-could-join-png-in-rlwc/news-story/a4dea0d63b5fe0baee0f8e87134fd9a2|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref>

