{{Orphan|date=April 2016}}

'''Terminal lucidity''' refers to an unexpected return of mental clarity and memory that occurs in the time shortly before death in patients suffering from severe [[Mental disorder|psychiatric]] or [[Neurological disorder|neurological disorders]]. This phenomenon has been noted in patients with [[schizophrenia]], [[Neoplasm|tumors]], [[stroke]]s, [[meningitis]], [[Parkinson's disease]], and [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.archger.2011.06.031 |pmid=21764150 |title=Terminal lucidity: A review and a case collection |journal=Archives of Gerontology and Geriatrics |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=138–42 |year=2012 |last1=Nahm |first1=Michael |last2=Greyson |first2=Bruce |last3=Kelly |first3=Emily Williams |last4=Haraldsson |first4=Erlendur }}</ref>

It may be present even in cases of patients with previous mental disability.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2190/OM.68.1.e |pmid=24547666 |title=The Death of Anna Katharina Ehmer: A Case Study in Terminal Lucidity |journal=OMEGA |volume=68 |issue=1 |pages=77–87 |year=2014 |last1=Nahm |first1=M. |last2=Greyson |first2=B. }}</ref> There are two subtypes: one that comes gradually (a week before death), and another that comes rapidly (hours before death). The former occurs in the majority of cases. There may be plenty of cases reported in literature, although the phrase terminal lucidity was coined in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bering |first1=Jesse |year=2017 |title=One Last Goodbye: The Strange Case of Terminal Lucidity |work=Scientific American Blog Network |url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/bering-in-mind/one-last-goodbye-the-strange-case-of-terminal-lucidity/ }}</ref>

