'''William Hogan''' (July 17, 1792 &ndash; November 25, 1874) was a [[United States Representative]] from [[New York (state)|New York]]. He was born in the parish of St. Paul's Convent Garden, [[London, England]], on July 17, 1792. His father, [[Michael Hogan (shipowner)|Michael Hogan]], was an Irish merchant and shipowner, who sailed with his family between Britain, South Africa, India, China and Australia. Hogan's mother was Frances Richardson Hogan, the illegitimate daughter of William Richardson, a merchant who based in Bombay who Michael Hogan worked with and Anna Lacy, Richardson's housekeeper who was of at least partial native Indian descent. In 1803, Hogan senior and his family settled in [[New York City]].
Hogan pursued classical studies and graduated from [[Columbia University|Columbia College]] in 1811. He served in the [[War of 1812]] and fought in the [[Battle of Plattsburgh]]. He studied law, was admitted to the bar but did not engage in practice.
He served as a member of the [[New York State Assembly]], was county judge of [[Franklin County, New York|Franklin County]], and was elected as a [[Jacksonian Party (United States)|Jacksonian]] to the Twenty-second Congress (March 4, 1831 – March 3, 1833). Hogan was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1832 to the Twenty-third Congress. He was appointed examiner of claims on March 30, 1855, and subsequently became a translator in the [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]], serving until October 8, 1869. He died in [[Washington, D.C.]] on November 25, 1874, with interment in [[Trinity Church Cemetery]], New York City.
